    <!-- SECTION 6: WHY MELATONIN ISN'T WORKING -->
    <h2>Why Melatonin Is Not Working for You: 7 Common Reasons</h2>

    <p>If you have been taking melatonin and it does not seem to help, do not assume the supplement is useless. In most cases, melatonin failure is caused by one or more correctable factors. Here are the seven most common reasons melatonin underperforms — and what to do about each one.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="clock" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>1. You Are Taking It Too Late</h4>
        <p>Taking melatonin as you get into bed is the number one mistake. By the time it absorbs and reaches peak levels (30-60 minutes), you have already been lying awake long enough to feel frustrated — which triggers cortisol and makes sleep even harder. Take melatonin 30-60 minutes before bed, not at bedtime.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>2. Your Dose Is Too High</h4>
        <p>Doses above 3-5mg produce blood levels far beyond what the body naturally produces. This can cause vivid dreams, next-day grogginess, and receptor desensitization. Try reducing your dose to 0.5-1mg. Many people who failed at 5-10mg find lower doses more effective. Read more about safe dosing in our guide on <a href="/blog/how-many-melatonin-gummies-should-i-take/">how many melatonin gummies to take</a>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="sun" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>3. You Are Exposed to Light After Taking It</h4>
        <p>Scrolling your phone in bed after taking melatonin is like turning on a sprinkler while trying to start a fire. Blue light from screens directly suppresses melatonin receptor activation. Put screens away after taking melatonin. No exceptions.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="droplet" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>4. You Took It After a Big Meal</h4>
        <p>A full stomach — especially a high-fat meal — delays melatonin absorption by up to 30 minutes or more. The supplement competes with food for intestinal absorption. Take melatonin on an empty stomach or at least 60 minutes after eating for optimal absorption speed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="trending" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>5. Your Sleep Issue Is Not Circadian</h4>
        <p>Melatonin addresses circadian rhythm misalignment — it tells your brain what time it is. But if your insomnia is caused by anxiety, pain, sleep apnea, restless legs, or medication side effects, melatonin does not address the root cause. For anxiety-driven insomnia, magnesium glycinate or <a href="/sleep/l-theanine-gummies/">L-theanine</a> may be more effective.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="bar" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>6. You Are Inconsistent</h4>
        <p>Taking melatonin sporadically — only on nights when you cannot sleep — undermines its circadian function. Melatonin works best as a consistent nightly signal that trains your body's internal clock. Use it at the same time every night for at least 2 weeks before evaluating whether it works.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>7. Your Product Has Inaccurate Dosing</h4>
        <p>A 2017 study in the <em>Journal of Clinical Sleep Medicine</em> found that 71% of melatonin supplements tested did not contain the amount stated on the label. Some had 83% less melatonin than advertised; others had 478% more. Choose products with third-party testing (USP, NSF, or ConsumerLab verified) to ensure dose accuracy.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">⚠️</span>
      <p><strong>When to see a doctor:</strong> If you have followed the optimal timing protocol, tried different doses (0.5-3mg), eliminated light exposure, and melatonin still does not help after 2-3 weeks of consistent use, consult a sleep medicine physician. Persistent insomnia can be a symptom of obstructive sleep apnea, restless legs syndrome, or other treatable conditions that melatonin cannot address.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SECTION 7: HOW LONG DOES MELATONIN STAY IN YOUR SYSTEM? -->
    <h2>How Long Does Melatonin Stay in Your System?</h2>

    <p>Melatonin is metabolized quickly. Understanding its half-life and clearance time helps you predict how long the effects will last and whether it will cause next-day grogginess.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">40-60 min</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">is the elimination half-life of melatonin — meaning half the dose is cleared from your bloodstream every 40-60 minutes. After 4-5 half-lives (approximately 4-5 hours), melatonin is essentially eliminated from your system. <strong>Source: Clinical pharmacokinetic studies published in the Journal of Pineal Research.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <p>Here is what happens after you take melatonin, based on a standard immediate-release 3mg dose:</p>

    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Time After Ingestion</th>
            <th>Approximate Blood Level</th>
            <th>What You Feel</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>0-30 minutes</strong></td>
            <td>Rising (absorption phase)</td>
            <td>Little to no effect yet</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>30-60 minutes</strong></td>
            <td>Peak (T-max)</td>
            <td>Maximum drowsiness and sleep readiness</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>1-2 hours</strong></td>
            <td>Declining (~50% of peak)</td>
            <td>Sleep onset window — most people are asleep</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>2-3 hours</strong></td>
            <td>Low (~25% of peak)</td>
            <td>Minimal residual effect</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>4-5 hours</strong></td>
            <td>Near zero (cleared)</td>
            <td>No residual effect — fully metabolized</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>This short duration is why melatonin is effective for <em>falling</em> asleep but not for <em>staying</em> asleep. If you fall asleep within the first 1-2 hours but wake at 2-3 AM, melatonin has already cleared your system. For sleep maintenance issues, extended-release melatonin formulations or complementary supplements like <a href="/blog/magnesium-for-sleep/">magnesium</a> (which has a much longer duration of action) may be more appropriate.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-box-ico">💡</span>
      <p><strong>Next-day grogginess:</strong> Because melatonin clears in 4-5 hours, it should not cause morning grogginess at appropriate doses (0.5-3mg). If you feel groggy the next day, your dose is likely too high. Reduce by half and reassess. Doses of 5mg+ can cause lingering drowsiness, especially in slow metabolizers and older adults.</p>
    </div>

