    <!-- SECTION 8: MELATONIN FOR DIFFERENT SLEEP PROBLEMS -->
    <h2>Melatonin Timing for Different Sleep Problems</h2>

    <p>Not all sleep problems are the same, and the optimal melatonin timing depends on which specific issue you are trying to solve. Melatonin is most effective for circadian-related problems and less effective for anxiety-driven or pain-driven insomnia. Here is the evidence-based timing for each scenario:</p>

    <div class="tbl-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Sleep Problem</th>
            <th>When to Take Melatonin</th>
            <th>Recommended Dose</th>
            <th>Expected Effectiveness</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Difficulty falling asleep</strong></td>
            <td>30-60 min before desired sleep time</td>
            <td>0.5-3mg</td>
            <td>High — melatonin's primary use case</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Jet lag (eastward travel)</strong></td>
            <td>At local bedtime at destination for 3-5 nights</td>
            <td>0.5-3mg</td>
            <td>Very high — strongest clinical evidence</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Jet lag (westward travel)</strong></td>
            <td>At local bedtime if waking too early</td>
            <td>0.5-1mg</td>
            <td>Moderate — westward adaptation is easier</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Shift work</strong></td>
            <td>30 min before desired daytime sleep</td>
            <td>1-3mg</td>
            <td>High — combine with blackout curtains</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="hl">
            <td><strong>Delayed sleep phase (night owl)</strong></td>
            <td>3-5 hours before current natural sleep time</td>
            <td>0.3-0.5mg (low dose)</td>
            <td>High — advance circadian clock gradually</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Staying asleep (middle-of-night waking)</strong></td>
            <td>Extended-release at bedtime; or 0.5mg upon waking</td>
            <td>2mg extended-release</td>
            <td>Low-Moderate — consider adding magnesium</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>Notice that the timing and dose are different for each problem. Delayed sleep phase disorder (the "night owl" pattern) requires an especially nuanced approach — a very low dose (0.3-0.5mg) taken much earlier in the evening (3-5 hours before current sleep time) to gradually shift the circadian clock earlier. Taking a large dose at bedtime does nothing to address the underlying circadian misalignment.</p>

    <p>For shift workers who need to sleep during the day, melatonin is one of the most evidence-based interventions available. The Cochrane Database review of melatonin and shift work found consistent benefits when 1-3mg was taken 30 minutes before desired daytime sleep, combined with blackout curtains and avoidance of bright light after the shift ends. For the best gummy options for shift workers and other sleep challenges, explore our ranked guide to the <a href="/best-sleep-gummies/">best sleep gummies</a>.</p>

