    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>How Long Does Melatonin Take to Work — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How long does melatonin take to kick in?</summary><p>Melatonin typically takes 30 to 60 minutes to produce noticeable drowsiness. Liquid melatonin works fastest (15-30 minutes), followed by sublingual tablets (20-30 minutes), gummies (30-45 minutes), and standard tablets (45-60 minutes). Taking melatonin on an empty stomach speeds absorption. Plan to take your dose 30-60 minutes before your desired bedtime.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Should I take melatonin 30 or 60 minutes before bed?</summary><p>For gummies or standard tablets, aim for 45-60 minutes before bed. For liquid or sublingual forms, 30 minutes is sufficient. The key is consistency — take melatonin at the same time each night relative to your target sleep time. If you eat dinner late, add 15-20 minutes to allow for delayed absorption.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Why doesn't melatonin work for me?</summary><p>The most common reasons are: taking it too late (at bedtime instead of 30-60 minutes before), using too high a dose (try reducing to 0.5-1mg), screen exposure after taking it, eating a large meal close to bedtime, or having a sleep issue that melatonin does not address (anxiety, sleep apnea, chronic pain). Try the full timing protocol in this guide for 2 weeks before concluding melatonin does not work for you.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Does a higher dose of melatonin work faster?</summary><p>No. The time to peak blood levels is determined by absorption rate, not dose. A 0.5mg dose reaches peak concentration at approximately the same time as a 10mg dose. Research shows 0.5-3mg is as effective as higher doses for most people. Supraphysiological doses (5-10mg) can cause receptor desensitization, vivid dreams, and next-day grogginess without faster onset.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How long does melatonin stay in your system?</summary><p>Melatonin has a half-life of 40-60 minutes and is fully cleared from the body in approximately 4-5 hours. This short duration is why melatonin helps you fall asleep but may not help you stay asleep. For sleep maintenance issues, extended-release melatonin or magnesium glycinate supplementation may be more appropriate.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Is it OK to take melatonin every night?</summary><p>Short-term nightly use (up to 3 months) is considered safe at 0.5-5mg for most adults. Unlike prescription sleep aids, melatonin does not cause physical dependence or withdrawal. Long-term studies (up to 2 years) have not shown significant adverse effects. However, if you need melatonin every night for months, consult your doctor to investigate underlying sleep disorders.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do melatonin gummies work as fast as pills?</summary><p>Gummies are slightly slower than pills. Gummies require chewing and gastric digestion (30-45 minute onset), while sublingual tablets bypass digestion (20-30 minutes) and liquid is fastest (15-30 minutes). Standard tablets take 45-60 minutes. The 15-20 minute difference is usually not significant if you time your dose correctly. Gummies offer the highest compliance due to taste.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take melatonin if I wake up in the middle of the night?</summary><p>You can take a low dose (0.5-1mg) if you have at least 4-5 hours of sleep time remaining. Since melatonin stays in your system for 4-5 hours, taking it with fewer than 4 hours until your alarm risks morning grogginess. A better long-term strategy for middle-of-the-night awakenings is extended-release melatonin at bedtime or magnesium glycinate supplementation.</p></details>
    </section>

